&lt;p style=&quot;font-weight: 400;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Abstract&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The kernel memset() function is one of the most critical and frequently used functions. One of its important uses is in creating zeroed pages. However, zeroing a huge page is an expensive operation: for example, the memset() takes 320 milliseconds for zeroing a 2GB huge page on an Oracle SPARC M7 processor running Linux. Since big-memory applications such as in memory databases require hundreds of huge pages, the overhead of creating huge pages significantly impacts application startup times and as well as runtime performance. To alleviate this problem, we develop a hybrid memset() function that exploits hardware accelerators available on modern multi-core systems to quickly fill memory (e.g., zeroing huge pages) and improve database startup times by up to 6.0x and JVM Garbage Collector latencies by up to 4.0x.&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;font-weight: 400;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Speaker&#39;s profile:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;font-weight: 400;&quot;&gt;Kishore&amp;rsquo;s PhD dissertation research work and also overall 10+ years of Industry work are all about developing self-learning software systems to achieve high performance for emerging BigData applications. His research interests are Autonomous Systems, Operating Systems, Data Science, Applied Machine Learning, Distributed Systems, and Natural Language Processing. He is the author of 16 peer-reviewed conference/journal publications and 4 patents. Currently he is an adjunct professor at Santa Clara University: teach Data Science, Distributed Systems, and Applied Machine Learning and research on Natural Language Processing tools.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Abstract:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;The lecture will delve into what a cloud is &amp;nbsp; with focus on how cloudstack can help get a &amp;nbsp; private cloud up and running.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;CloudStack is a turnkey solution that includes the entire &amp;ldquo;stack&amp;rdquo; of features, most organizations want with an IaaS cloud: compute orchestration, Network-as-a-Service, user and account management, a full and open native API, resource accounting, and a first class User Interface (UI).&lt;/p&gt;
